<title type="html"><![CDATA[GBS files]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=268&amp;p=3574#p3574"><![CDATA[
I'm assuming you use a Game Boy emulator initially, make the GBS rip, then clean it up using a GBS-to-GB ROM utility so you can use a Game Boy debugger.<br /><br />To help with GBS rips, I am working on a simple command-line GBS checker/debugger using my GBS playback library. I was thinking of cleaning it up and working with someone on the PC side to release an executable. The idea is that you use this as a final check of a GBS file. It checks the header for extra bits set (people often set the timer bytes wrong, for example), reports unmapped memory accesses, bad bank selection, etc. You can do basic stepping, disassembly, and breakpoints, which are enough to debug those last problems that you don't catch with the GBS-to-ROM testing.<br /><br />Would this be useful? It's been on the back burner for a while and it'd be nice to make something of it. It could have a basic GUI, depending on whoever does the PC shell for it.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Tue Aug 09, 2005 12:33 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
